			<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; " >
												<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Jarroll wrote:<BR>
<DIV>On another note, how many people do you know that could tell their boss or customers "nay, we aren't going to do that because it would take some time or is difficult."&nbsp;&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Get over yourselves.&nbsp; You aren't a monopoly anymore.&nbsp; You can't have the mentality that you are.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV>Um, I think I speak for just about everyone in the software field when I say we do this all the time! </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Working on a big project is incredibly complex. I know at my work we have the product group that actually writes the SRS (software requirement specifications), the development group that implements the SRS, the QA group that does testing in parallel based upon those specs, the documentation team that writes about the changes before they even occur, the localization team that is responsible for seeing the changes translated for regional, language and cultural differences, the QA team that does the non code based bug testing, the tech reviews, the feedback reviews...I could go on and on.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>So when some seamingly simple request gets put forward by a client it has to go through an incredibly complex system to get implemented. Generally speaking a product is "feature complete" about 6 months before it is released (on a 12 month development cycle). For maintainance issues like this I know where I work it comes down to some developer having a bit of free time to implement a change. This doesn't even take into account they way they assign development tasks in a software firm (you tend to have 100's of hours of tasks scheduled ahead of time, so it is exceedingly rare to have "free time" to work on stuff).</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>This is why things work they way they do. Sometimes even seemingly simple changes can have huge effects. For instance, where I work a client suggested we change the X's in a feature list to Y's. But Y doesn't stand for Yes in every language so this would have massive localization problems, whereas X is universal. I'm not saying SoE works this way, but something that seems simple to us (just lower the damage) may be complex because it may turn out that the songs are actually hard coded to have one effect field and if you change the damage you end up nerfing the slow or tash component by the same amount.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
																		
										</td></tr>
